AB  - Based on a proprietary loan dataset from a nationwide state-owned Chinese commercial bank, this study finds that firms with high air pollutant emissions intensity are charged higher bank loan prices due to increased labor risk and environmental transition costs, which elevate bank lender’s overall risk exposure. The positive impact of such emissions on bank loan pricing is more pronounced in firms with no political connections, those located in regions with weak environmental governance, and classified as non-headquarter clients. Further analyses suggest that air pollution premiums are mainly charged for smoke emissions and credit loans. Moreover, air pollutant emissions significantly reduce the credit availability of borrowing firms and increase the tendency for bank lender to add non-price terms.
